More memoir than biography, Hersh’s book plumbs the sources of Chesnutt’s pain and creativity more deeply than any conventional account of his life and recordings ever could. Chesnutt was difficult to understand and frequently difficult to be with, but, as Hersh reveals him, he was also wickedly funny and painfully perceptive. This intimate memoir is essential reading for anyone interested in the music or the artist.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aChesnutt, Vic -- Anecdotes. 0aHersh, Kristin -- Anecdotes. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aPetrusich, Amanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311074533740uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/75947340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477308752423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477308752/original  a978-3-11-074533-7  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles